@node make-host-2.lisp
@section @file{make-host-2.lisp}
@cindex make-host-2.lisp


As in used in @file{make-host-1.lisp} @code{load} @file{shared.lisp}
sets @code{sb-xc:*features*} at the top level and
@file{set-up-cold-packages.lisp} and
@file{defun-load-or-cload-xcompiler.lisp} are loaded again as well.

@node set-up-cold-packages.lisp
@subsection set-up-cold-packages.lisp
@cindex set-up-cold-packages.lisp

@file{src/cold/set-up-cold-packages.lisp} is responsible for a lot of
package wizardry. It runs essentially in two modes `SBCL mode' in
which some symbols in @code{sb-cold} are connected to various other
SBCL native packages and in `CL compatability mode' where all symbols
are either inheritted from common lisp or defined in the package,
i.e. without using any implementation specific hidden system package
definitions.


The variable @code{*host-format-function-names*} help illuminate this
dynamic. The code comments has the following to say about it:

@cartouche
@quotation
The list below contains the name of every symbol whose function
might be called from a non-compiled format string. This is important
only for SBCL as host lisp built prior to git revision
6d743d78d9ba840b.  For such hosts, after giving all host packages a
new name, we must ASAP reestablish the function bindings of these
"missing" symbols.

@itemize

@item @code{print-symbol-with-prefix} was added in rev ff218a24fbd70b2e
(2007-04-29) and later exported from @code{sb-ext} with no
explanation.  It was occasionally invoked via SB-IMPL: which it no
longer is.

@item @code{sb-impl:print-type} and @code{sb-impl:print-type-specifier}
were first added in rev c1b03a36ec4439c8 (2016-01-09). Newer code
always uses them from @code{sb-impl} but older code used them from
@code{sb-ext} as well.

@end itemize

The other 3 functions mentioned below have been stable in that they
are always used from @code{sb-impl}.

This list must contain names of functions used by @emph{any} past
revision even if such function does not appear in current code.  The
list does not need additions to it for future changes
though. i.e. this is final.''

@end quotation
@end cartouche

And the following comment for @code{hide-host-packages} and
@code{unhide-host-format-funs}. When compiled by a non-SBCL CL these
are just empty stub functions:

@cartouche
@quotation
Rename all host packages, but unhide the host's format functions for
hosts that do not support renaming of internal packages.  Consider all
situations in which functions are called via ~// directives:

@itemize

@item The host calls ~/PRINT-TYPE/ for itself (i.e in its compiler) while
running make-host-1 because "our" code (being compiled) is wrong.
Barring a host bug (such as was fixed in rev e6fd2a9635e4), the format
string referencing this function would spell the name using a "dash"
package. We restore the format functions into the expected package
below.
   
@item The cross-compiler wants to call a ~// function while executing,
maybe even from a macro. The format control string should spell the
function as a "bang" package. If it didn't, the string is wrong.
   
@item The target wants to call a ~// function.
That's conceptually the easiest to deal with - we've already ensured
that cross-compiled format strings dump their symbols correctly.

@end itemize
@end quotation 
@end cartouche

In particular note that on occasion there are ``host functions that
are potentially called from format strings''. This magic is
accomplished by @code{preserving-host-function} which is a macro that
wraps the function and @code{restore-host-function} which provides the
machinery, again, for non-SBCL it is simply a no-op function.

@code{sb-cold:*shadows*} is a list of strings that indicate the
symbols that package @code{sb-cold} shadows. Most of them have to do
with numbers, types and compilation. Examples: @code{floatp},
@code{realp} @code{complexp} @code{numberp}
@code{array-dimension-limit} @code{array-rank-limit}
@code{array-total-size-limit} @code{char-code} @code{code-char}
@code{compile-file} @code{compile-file-pathname}
@code{*compile-file-pathname*}










